+# Mobile support plan
+
+Current state: every internal route under `/screens/*` is in the `desktop-only` bucket (see `src/data/route-buckets.ts`) → `Shell` renders `<MobileFallback />` instead of the real UI. Only `/login` and `/register` are `mobile-first`. The result is the "Best viewed on desktop" card the user saw on `tribe.learnmeld.com` from an iPhone.
+
+This doc lays out a phased plan to bring the app to a usable mobile state without breaking the desktop experience that's currently being iterated on.
+
+## Locked decisions (interactive planning session)
+
+| Decision | Choice |
+|---|---|
+| Mobile nav pattern | **Hybrid** — bottom tab bar (Vault / Pipeline / Settings) + hamburger drawer for everything else (workspace switcher, account, sign out, future destinations) |
+| Pipeline Kanban on mobile | **Vertical accordion** — all 5 stages stack as collapsible sections; current stage expanded by default |
+| PieceDetail on mobile | **Stack vertically** — FieldCards (LEFT) above the task checklist (RIGHT) in one continuous scroll |
+| Settings tabs on mobile | **Native `<select>` dropdown** — replaces the horizontal pill row at narrow widths |
+| Test strategy | **Automated Playwright at 390×844** as a second project — every test runs at both desktop AND mobile viewports, plus 2-3 mobile-specific smokes |
+| Rollout pacing | **Start now in parallel with SaaS testing.** Phase 1 (foundation) sequential. Phase 2 sub-items (Pipeline / PieceDetail / Settings) in parallel as 3 implementer agents. Phases 3 + 4 last. |
+
+These decisions are the contract for every phase below. Don't redebate them mid-implementation; bring them back here if they need to change.
+
+## Regression bookends — required around mobile work
+
+Mobile work touches enough shared surface (Sidebar, TopBar, Shell layout, route gating, modals, button padding) that a desktop regression is a real risk. To make sure we don't ship broken desktop while chasing mobile, the mobile cycle has bookends on both ends:
+
+**Before mobile work starts** — desktop regression baseline:
+- Run `npx playwright test --reporter=line` on `main` of `restructuring-saas-design` (no mobile project yet — just the existing 47 tests at desktop).
+- Result must be **47/47 pass**. Any flake or failure is fixed FIRST, before any Phase 1 code is touched. The audit is a planning step — the baseline check is the actual go/no-go gate for shipping.
+- This guards against the "we thought desktop was green but it wasn't" footgun.
+
+**After mobile work lands** — ongoing dual-viewport coverage:
+- From Phase 1 onward, `playwright.config.ts` has two projects (`chromium-desktop` and `chromium-mobile`). Every commit on `restructuring-saas-design` runs both. Every test runs twice.
+- Permanent invariant after Phase 1: **every commit ships only if BOTH projects are 100% green**. Single-viewport regressions block merge.
+- Each phase commit additionally requires a manual sanity sweep on real device (you on iPhone at `tribe.learnmeld.com`) covering: open Pipeline, open a piece, walk through Brainstorm fields, add a task, switch workspace via the drawer. Anything that visibly breaks gets a new test added under `tests/mobile-*` before the next phase ships.
+- This is the "loop" — desktop + mobile stay green simultaneously, in perpetuity, not just during the mobile rollout.
+
+The Phase 1 implementer is already adding the second Playwright project per the locked decision. The regression-bookend discipline above describes how we *use* it across this cycle and going forward.
+
+## Phase 0 — Audit (no shipping)
+
+Before changing anything, catalog where mobile breaks. Run through the app at ~390px width (iPhone 12/13/14 pro-class) and note every screen + interaction that needs work. Use Chrome DevTools device emulation while the dev server is running.
+
+Expected hits, grouped by screen, ranked by user impact:
+
+| Screen | Mobile issues today |
+|---|---|
+| `/screens/pipeline` (Kanban) | 5-column `grid-template-columns: repeat(5, minmax(220px, 1fr))` → horizontal scroll hell at 390px. Cards inside columns are fine. Empty state already centers ok. |
+| `/screens/piece/:id` (PieceDetail) | Header is OK. Platforms chips wrap. Stage tabs row may overflow. The LEFT (FieldCards stack) + RIGHT (TaskList) `flex: 1 / flex: 0 0 280px` two-column layout is the biggest blocker — RIGHT panel squeezes content. |
+| `/screens/vault` | Grid of vault cards — already wraps via CSS grid (`auto-fit, minmax`). Verify touch targets on hover-only affordances. |
+| `/screens/settings` | Horizontal tab list will overflow; need either a select dropdown for tabs OR horizontal scroll with visible scrollbar. |
+| Sidebar nav (`src/shell/Sidebar.tsx`) | Always-visible left rail — eats too much width on mobile. Needs hamburger / drawer pattern. |
+| TopBar (`src/shell/TopBar.tsx`) | AccountWorkspaceSwitcher dropdown + Sign out menu OK. Sign-out menu currently fits. |
+| Onboarding / register / login | Centered cards work on mobile — already mobile-first bucketed. Smoke check only. |
+| `/invite/:token`, `/share/recap/:token`, `/share/billing/:token` | Single-card layouts — likely fine. Smoke check only. |
+| Modals (AdvanceModal, AddTaskDialog, WorkspaceInviteModal) | All use `max-width: 420px` + flex centering — OK on mobile but lose padding on edges; review `width: 100%` + side margins. |
+
+After the audit, file each finding into one of three buckets: **Phase 1** (foundation), **Phase 2** (per-screen), **Phase 3** (polish).
+
+## Phase 1 — Foundation (1-2 days)
+
+### 1a. Drop the desktop-only blanket fallback for `/screens/*`
+
+`MobileFallback.tsx` currently hides every screen behind a "best viewed on desktop" card. Change the strategy:
+
+- **Keep MobileFallback as a per-screen opt-out**, not a default. Bucketize per route: most screens become `mobile-responsive`; the Kanban Pipeline stays `desktop-only` until Phase 2 lands its mobile layout.
+- Update `src/data/route-buckets.ts`:
+  ```
+  /screens/pipeline       → desktop-only   (until 2a ships)
+  /screens/piece/:id      → mobile-responsive
+  /screens/vault          → mobile-responsive
+  /screens/settings       → mobile-responsive
+  ```
+- `Shell.tsx` already calls `useIsMobile() + bucketForPath()`. The plumbing is in place — just flip the bucket values.
+
+### 1b. Hybrid nav on mobile — bottom tab bar + hamburger drawer
+
+`Sidebar.tsx` is rendered unconditionally. Need a media-query split:
+
+- ≥ 768px: current always-visible left rail (no change).
+- < 768px:
+  - **Bottom tab bar** fixed at the bottom of the viewport with 3 destinations: Vault / Pipeline / Settings. Each is a 56-ish-px tap target with an icon + label. The active tab is highlighted.
+  - **Hamburger drawer** (slide-in overlay from the left) holds everything else: workspace switcher, account menu, sign-out, any non-primary destinations added later. Triggered by a burger icon in the TopBar; dismissable via backdrop tap.
+  - Bottom safe-area padding so the bar respects iOS home-indicator gap.
+
+Implementation: a single `Sidebar` becomes responsive (rail on desktop, drawer-overlay on mobile). A new `BottomTabBar` component renders only at `useIsMobile()`. The drawer's open/closed state lives in the Shell (`useState`) since both TopBar (trigger) and Sidebar (target) need it.
+
+### 1c. Breakpoint constants + media-query helpers
+
+Right now most components use inline-style only — no media queries. For Phase 2, several components need responsive layout (LEFT/RIGHT panels stack on mobile, Kanban → vertical list, etc.). Two options:
+
+- **Option A**: Keep inline-style and use `useIsMobile()` to branch React render. Simple, no new tooling. Re-renders on resize.
+- **Option B**: Add a tiny CSS file (or extend `globals.css`) with one media query class per breakpoint we use. Components attach class names; CSS handles the layout switch with zero JS re-render cost.
+
+**Recommend Option A** for the demo phase — fewer moving parts, matches the existing inline-style vocabulary, and `useIsMobile()` already exists.
+
+Standardize one breakpoint constant (`MOBILE_BREAKPOINT_PX = 768`, already exists in `route-buckets.ts`). Don't introduce more without a reason.
+
+### 1d. Touch-target audit
+
+Minimum touch target: 44×44 px (Apple HIG) / 48×48 (Material). The codebase has plenty of 6×6 px × icons and tight checkboxes. Add a global Phase 1 sweep:
+
+- Task list × and pencil buttons (currently `padding: 0 2px` + `fontSize: 14` — needs minimum 32×32 hit area at least via padding).
+- Platforms chips in PieceDetail (currently `padding: 3px 10px` — bump to 6px vertical on mobile).
+- Stage tabs (verify).
+- AddTaskDialog close/save buttons (already 8×14 — OK).
+- Shot list × buttons.
+
+Do this with a single PR that adds padding to small interactive elements on mobile (gated via `useIsMobile()`).
+
+## Phase 2 — Per-screen mobile layouts (3-5 days)
+
+### 2a. Pipeline Kanban → vertical stack on mobile
+
+The 5-column grid is the worst offender. On mobile:
+
+- Render stages as a vertical accordion. Each stage is a collapsible section with its piece cards stacked. Default state: only the user's current stage expanded (or the stage with the most pieces).
+- Stage label + count badge in the accordion header.
+- Per-stage "+ New piece" button stays inside the accordion body.
+- Empty state (no pieces in any stage) — already centered card, works fine.
+
+File: `src/screens/Pipeline.tsx`. Branch on `useIsMobile()` and render an accordion variant.
+
+### 2b. PieceDetail LEFT/RIGHT → stacked on mobile
+
+Two-column flex doesn't fit. On mobile:
+
+- Stack LEFT (FieldCards) above RIGHT (TaskList) in a single column.
+- LEFT panel keeps its FieldCard stack.
+- RIGHT panel (task list) becomes a collapsible "Tasks" section that defaults to expanded. Tap to collapse if it gets in the way.
+
+Alternative: a tab switcher at the top — "Content" / "Tasks". Probably overkill; stacking is simpler.
+
+File: `src/components/production/StageWorkspace.tsx`. Branch the flex container on `useIsMobile()`: `flexDirection: column` + `flex: 1` for both children + reasonable max-heights so neither dominates.
+
+### 2c. Settings tabs → native `<select>` dropdown on mobile
+
+A real `<select>` element of tabs at the top of the Settings page on mobile, vs the horizontal pill row on desktop. The native OS picker handles selection. The active tab's content stays the same below.
+
+File: `src/screens/Settings.tsx`. Branch the tabs renderer on `useIsMobile()`.
+
+### 2d. Vault grid → single column on narrow screens
+
+Already mostly auto-fitting via CSS grid — verify it falls back to a single column at 390px. May need to tweak `minmax(220px, 1fr)` → `minmax(180px, 1fr)`.
+
+### 2e. Modal full-bleed on mobile
+
+`AdvanceModal`, `AddTaskDialog`, `WorkspaceInviteModal` use `max-width: 420px` centered. On mobile, this leaves no horizontal margin; the card touches the screen edges via `width: 100%`. Add `margin: 16px` outside the card so the backdrop is visible on the sides — easier to dismiss via backdrop tap.
+
+## Phase 3 — Polish + edge cases (2 days)
+
+### 3a. Hours-spent input — mobile keyboard
+
+The number input on the per-stage strip currently uses `type="number"`. On iOS this triggers the numeric keyboard but with a decimal pad you need `inputMode="decimal"` for 0.25h precision. Add it.
+
+### 3b. Inline title edit on mobile
+
+Hover-reveal of the pencil doesn't work on touch. On mobile, either always show the pencil OR make the title text itself fully tappable. Simpler: drop the hover-reveal on mobile and show the pencil unconditionally.
+
+### 3c. Platforms chips wrapping behavior
+
+At very narrow widths the chips may wrap to a second row. Verify and tune `flex-wrap` + gap.
+
+### 3d. Long titles in breadcrumbs / cards
+
+`max-width: 320px` + `text-overflow: ellipsis` already on the breadcrumb's plain-text segment. Verify card titles, AW switcher labels, and stage tab labels also elide gracefully.
+
+### 3e. Drag-and-drop (`@dnd-kit/...`) on touch
+
+`react-icons` plus `@dnd-kit/core` is already in package.json. If any drag-reorder UI is wired to vault cards or pipeline columns, verify touch support — `@dnd-kit` has separate sensors for touch (`TouchSensor` vs `PointerSensor`). Audit + fix as needed.
+
+## Phase 4 — Test coverage (1 day)
+
+Note: the Playwright mobile project itself is added during Phase 1 per the locked rollout decision. Phase 4 finalises the **mobile-specific smokes** + makes the dual-project run a permanent invariant.
+
+Add these mobile-specific smokes:
+- `tests/mobile-pipeline-accordion.spec.ts`: Kanban accordion expands/collapses; tapping a stage header reveals its pieces.
+- `tests/mobile-piece-detail-stack.spec.ts`: LEFT/RIGHT panels stack vertically; advance flow still works.
+- `tests/mobile-sidebar-drawer.spec.ts`: hamburger toggles the drawer overlay; bottom tab bar highlights the active destination.
+
+**Post-Phase-4 invariant** (the loop):
+- Every commit on `restructuring-saas-design` must run **both Playwright projects** and **both must be 100% green** to merge / deploy.
+- Each shipped phase additionally requires a 60-second manual sweep on iPhone (you, at `tribe.learnmeld.com`): drawer → bottom tabs → Pipeline accordion → piece detail stacked → add task → switch workspace. Any visible break gets a new `tests/mobile-*` test in the same PR that fixes it.
+- Treat dual-viewport green as a release gate, not a nice-to-have. Single-viewport regressions get caught here instead of in the user's hand.
+
+## Automated regression loop (fan-out agents)
+
+After each phase ships (commit + deploy), kick off a parallel fan-out of regression agents that exhaustively exercises every feature at both viewports. Output: a regression report that drives the next fix cycle. Repeat until the report comes back clean.
+
+**The fan-out shape (5 agents in parallel, sonnet each):**
+
+| Agent | Owns | Sample tests it runs |
+|---|---|---|
+| auth-regression | Register / Login / Onboarding / Logout / Invite-accept flows | onboarding.spec, logout.spec, invite-flow.spec at both viewports |
+| pipeline-regression | Pipeline screen — Kanban (desktop), accordion (mobile), empty state, create piece, advance flow | production-smoke.spec, snapshot-isolation.spec, hours-spent.spec, stage-panel-rework.spec, mobile-pipeline-accordion.spec |
+| piece-detail-regression | PieceDetail header / platforms / hours / per-stage fields / task panel / inline title edit / modal | piece-title-edit.spec, task-add-popup.spec, task-edit-system-and-checklist.spec, mobile-piece-detail-stack.spec |
+| workspace-regression | Workspace isolation, AccountWorkspace switcher, Clients + share routes, Settings tabs | workspace-isolation.spec, aw-switcher.spec, clients-and-shares.spec, task-library.spec |
+| chrome-regression | Sidebar drawer + bottom tab bar + responsive shell + breakpoint behaviour | mobile-sidebar-drawer.spec + visual probes across all the above |
+
+Each agent gets the same brief shape:
+1. Run its assigned Playwright tests at BOTH `chromium-desktop` and `chromium-mobile` projects (project-filter on Playwright CLI).
+2. Read each failure's `error-context.md` and trace through the offending source file at the relevant line range.
+3. For its assigned feature area only, also do 3-5 "manual-style" probes via `mcp__plugin_playwright_playwright__browser_navigate` + screenshot + DOM inspect at both viewports — catches issues the automated tests miss (overflow, hidden buttons, ugly stacking).
+4. Output a structured finding list with: severity, surface (file:line), what breaks, suggested fix. Finding lists from all 5 agents get concatenated into a single regression report.
+
+**Then a fixup agent (sonnet) consumes the report:**
+- Applies fixes for all Blocker + Major findings inline.
+- Re-runs the full dual-viewport Playwright suite to verify.
+- Surfaces any Minor findings as TODO comments in the relevant file.
+- Outputs a summary mapping each finding → resolution.
+
+**Repeat the loop** until the next regression-fan-out report comes back clean. Each iteration commits its fixes with a `chore(regression): fix N findings from cycle K` message.
+
+**When to trigger the loop:**
+- **After each phase commit** (Phase 1, Phase 2, Phase 3, Phase 4) — non-blocking; the phase ships first, the loop catches anything that slipped. Each post-phase cycle is scoped to the features that phase actually touched plus any high-traffic surface (PieceDetail, Pipeline). Output gets concatenated to `docs/regression-log.md`.
+- **Final exhaustive cycle after Phase 4** — once all phases have shipped and the mobile rollout is "done", trigger one more fan-out that exercises EVERY feature at BOTH viewports with no scope filter. This is the comprehensive desktop-AND-mobile sweep that proves the mobile cycle didn't regress anything desktop while landing the new mobile surfaces. Same 5-agent shape, same fixup-agent follow-on, looped until clean.
+- **Manual testing follows the final automated cycle** — once the post-Phase-4 fan-out is clean, you do the human pass on real device. The manual sweep at this point isn't catching bugs (the automated loop already did); it's confirming the *feel* — animation smoothness, drawer slide-in latency, tab-bar tap response, anything that automated tests can't perceive. Manual is the explicit human gate to declare the mobile cycle "done".
+- **Before any major user demo** — pre-flight check using the same 5-agent fan-out, narrower scope. **You trigger it explicitly** ("I'm demoing in 30 min, run the regression loop on auth + workspace"). I dispatch the fan-out, surface findings to you in chat with severity grouping, and wait for your call on the fixup cycle.
+- **Weekly during active development** — drift catcher. Runs on a `/schedule` cron (Monday morning) WITHOUT my direct involvement, but **always sends you a summary message** with: cycle date, agents that ran, finding count by severity, link to `docs/regression-log.md` entry, and a 1-line headline ("clean", "3 minor", "1 major + 5 minor — recommend cycle 2"). You decide whether to trigger a fixup cycle from the summary; nothing auto-fixes weekly.
+
+**Keep-user-in-loop policy — applies to ALL trigger variants:**
+- No fully autonomous runs that ship fixes without your visibility.
+- Per-phase + final-exhaustive cycles: surface the regression report to you BEFORE the fixup agent dispatches. You see findings → confirm → I run fixups.
+- Pre-demo + weekly: you receive a summary message; you choose to act or not.
+- Manual sweep stays as the final human gate — automated loops never replace it for "done" declarations.
+
+**Why fan-out instead of one giant agent:**
+- Parallelism: 5 agents finish in ~the time of 1.
+- Scope isolation: each agent stays focused, doesn't get lost in unrelated test failures.
+- Output structure: each agent produces a structured slice of findings; the fixup agent consumes a well-formed list.
+- Cost-tier discipline (per the project's model-selection rule): all 5 are execute-tier work → sonnet. No opus needed here.
+
+**Where the regression loop output lives:**
+- Each cycle appends to `docs/regression-log.md` (new file, created on first run) with cycle number, date, findings, resolutions, follow-ups.
+- Recurring findings across cycles signal genuine bugs that need a real fix, not just a patch — flag them in the log.
+
+## Estimated total
+
+~7–10 days for full mobile support including tests and polish. Phases can interleave — Phase 2 sub-tasks are mostly independent and parallelize cleanly via the same dispatch pattern we've been using for the SaaS phases.
+
+## Recommended ordering
+
+1. **Phase 0 audit** (one focused agent-Explore session, ~30 min). Output: a finalized issue list grouped by phase.
+2. **Phase 1a** (route bucket flip + drop the global fallback). Unblocks everyone testing mobile screens that already work (login, register, share routes).
+3. **Phase 1b + 1c + 1d in parallel** — sidebar drawer + touch-target sweep + useIsMobile hook adoption.
+4. **Phase 2** items in parallel (Pipeline Kanban, PieceDetail stack, Settings dropdown, Modals).
+5. **Phase 3 polish** + **Phase 4 tests**.
+
+## Out of scope (for this cycle)
+
+- Native app (React Native / Capacitor) — not on the roadmap.
+- PWA install prompt / offline support — separate concern.
+- Mobile-specific feature work (camera capture for piece thumbnails, etc.) — that's product work; this plan is about responsive parity only.
+- iOS Safari quirks (100vh, safe-area-insets) — Phase 3e if needed.
+
+## Anti-patterns to avoid
+
+- **Don't introduce Tailwind / a CSS-in-JS lib** mid-cycle just for mobile. Stick with the inline-style + CSS-variables vocabulary already established.
+- **Don't refactor desktop layouts** while adding mobile. Branch via `useIsMobile()` for now; refactor later when both code paths have stabilized.
+- **Don't ship Phase 2 without Phase 1.** Stacking before fixing the sidebar drawer means the sidebar still takes up width on the stacked screens.
+- **Don't add a "mobile app" feature flag.** Just use viewport-driven rendering — feature flags accumulate and rot.
+
+## Phase 0 audit findings
+
+Generated 2026-05-23 by Explore agent reading every relevant file. File:line refs are the canonical targets for Phase 1+2 implementers.
+
+### Phase 1 — Foundation
+
+**F1-1 | Blocker | `src/data/route-buckets.ts:10-13` + `src/shell/Shell.tsx:31`**
+`ROUTE_BUCKETS` only contains `/login` and `/register`. Everything else falls through to the `desktop-only` default in `bucketForPath()`. `Shell.tsx:31` blocks anything that is not `mobile-first` — that is the "Best viewed on desktop" wall. Fix: add four entries to `ROUTE_BUCKETS`:
+- `/screens/piece/` → `mobile-responsive`
+- `/screens/vault` → `mobile-responsive`
+- `/screens/settings` → `mobile-responsive`
+- `/screens/pipeline` → keep `desktop-only` until Phase 2a ships
+
+No logic changes needed in `Shell.tsx`; the guard already reads the bucket.
+
+**F1-2 | Blocker | `src/shell/Sidebar.tsx:74-87`**
+`<aside>` has `width: 232`, `flexShrink: 0`, no `useIsMobile()` branch. At 390px it consumes 60% of horizontal space. `Shell.tsx:36` outer `display: flex` means sidebar + `<main>` share a fixed row with no wrapping. Removing MobileFallback for `/screens/piece/*` today reveals a sidebar eating ~232px leaving only ~158px for content. Fix: gate the `<aside>` render on `!isMobile`. Replacement nav (bottom tabs + drawer) lands in the same PR.
+
+**F1-3 | Major | `src/shell/TopBar.tsx:71-82` + `src/shell/AccountWorkspaceSwitcher.tsx:118-153`**
+TopBar `padding: 12px 24px` and always-present AW switcher pill render full-width. AW label renders `orgName · workspaceName` with no `maxWidth`/overflow guard (line 136). At 390px with a long org+workspace name the pill expands and pushes the avatar off-screen. Fix: add `maxWidth: 160px`, `overflow: hidden`, `textOverflow: ellipsis` to the label `<span>`; reduce TopBar side padding to `12px` on mobile. **No hamburger exists today** — Phase 1 must add a new burger icon button in TopBar that sets `drawerOpen` state in Shell.
+
+**F1-4 | Major | `src/components/production/TaskList.tsx:154-170 + 175-186`**
