+# Workspace Jurisdiction Implementation Plan
+
+> **For agentic workers:** REQUIRED SUB-SKILL: Use superpowers:subagent-driven-development (recommended) or superpowers:executing-plans to implement this plan task-by-task. Steps use checkbox (`- [ ]`) syntax for tracking.
+
+**Goal:** Introduce a per-workspace `jurisdiction` (set once at onboarding, immutable after) that scopes country-specific compliance features (ZATCA for Saudi Arabia today) and supplies currency/VAT/tax-id/suggested-language defaults via an extensible registry — and wire the ZATCA settings section into the existing AR/EN i18n so it follows the user's language preference instead of being hardcoded English.
+
+**Architecture:** Two orthogonal axes — per-user `language` (`prefs.language`, drives UI text + RTL) and per-workspace `jurisdiction` (drives features + defaults). A registry module (`src/data/jurisdictions.ts`) maps `'SA' | 'INTL'` to config. Feature-gating becomes `hasFeature(ws, 'zatca')`. Legacy `country`/`locale` fields are read once by a v2 migration to infer jurisdiction, then deleted. Jurisdiction never writes language at render time; it only *seeds* the initial language once at first-run onboarding.
+
+**Tech Stack:** React 18 + Vite + TypeScript strict (`noUnusedLocals`, `noUnusedParameters`), localStorage-backed stores (listeners + `useSyncExternalStore`-style hooks), flat-dotted-key i18n dictionaries, Playwright smoke tests (the project's only test framework — there is no unit-test runner, so logic units are verified by `tsc` + Playwright integration smokes).
+
+**Spec:** `docs/superpowers/specs/2026-05-23-workspace-jurisdiction-design.md` (Appendix A holds the drafted Arabic strings used verbatim in Task 2).
